Benchmark cases for MHD buoyant 2D cavity

Physics:
Cavity in y-z coordinates
U flows in x direction (also gravity)
B field in y direction 
Temperature gradient can be parallel (top-bottom walls) or perpendicular (left-right walls)

Boundary conditions:
Cyclic in x
Walls in y and z
U: no slip
p: zero gradient
electric potential:
    Conductive walls  -> zero gradient
    (1) Parallel case: Temperature gradient y direction
    (2) Perpendicular case: Temperature gradient z direction

Non-dimensional quantities:
Hartmann 500   = L*By*sqrt(sigma/(rho*nu))  [L = 1; By = 500; rho = 1; sigma = 0.001; nu = 0.001] 
Grassof 10^4  = g*beta*(Th-Tc)*L^3/nu^2     [g = 1; beta = 0.01; Th-Tc = 1; L = 1; nu = 0.001] 

Discretisation used in example:
Nx = 1
Ny = 30
Nz = 15
(97-3;10-90; 10) in Y direction -> 97% of the domain (bulk) discretized with 10% of the CV; 3% of the rest of the domain (wall mesh) contains the 90% of the CV with an aspect ratio of 10 between the smallest and largest CV inside this layer.
                                -> This mesh is used to properly resolve the Hartmann boundary layers.

Unconditionally stable symmetry-preserving operators are used.
Temporal discretisation is RK3 with fixed dt = 0.00005s.
Solver parameters can all be found in system/fvSolution

Analytical solution:
An analytical solution for the gradient of the transverse velocity W at the cavity center exists for 
    (1) The perpendicular case (temperature gradient and B perpendicular): dW/dZ = -Gr/2Ha
    (2) The parallel case (temperature gradient and B parallel): dW/dZ = -Gr/Ha^2
when Ha >> 1. W and Z denote the dimensionless transverse velocity and coordinate in the direction of the tempreature gradient, respectively non-dimensionalized by nu/L and L.
These solutions are given in T. Tagawa, G. Authié and R. Moreau 2002 - Buoyant flow in long vertical enclosures in the presence of a strong horizontal magnetic field. Part 1. Fully-established flow.

Run and post-process the case with:
./run.sh <case>
or
./parallelrun.sh <case>
where <case> is "perpendicular" or 'parallel'.

Example result for the perpendicular case are shown in the output:

Validation results
------------------
Boundary condition  = perpendicular
Probe file          = postProcessing/sampleB/0/grad(U)
Tensor component    = 7
Analytical solution = 10
Numerical solution  = 10.0752939
